nfamous criminals who passed through the penitentiary from 1934 to 1948. Ward, who enjoyed unprecedented access to FBI, Federal Bureau of Prisons, and Federal Parole records, conducted interviews with one hundred former Alcatraz convicts, guards, and administrators to produce this definitive history of "The Rock." Alcatraz is the only book with authoritative answers to questions that have swirled about the prison: How did prisoners cope psychologically with the harsh regime? What provoked the protests and strikes? How did security flaws lead to the sensational escape attempts? And what happened when these "habitual, incorrigible" convicts were finally released? By shining a light on the most famous prison in the world, Ward also raises timely questions about today's supermax prisons.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aPrisonszCaliforniazAlcatraz IslandxHistory. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  a20th century american crime.  a20th century american history.  aal capone.  aalcatraz.  aalvin karpis.  aamerican government.  aconvicts.  acrime.  adock barker.  aescape attempts.  afbi.  afederal bureau of prisons.  afederal government.  afederal parole records.  agangsters.  ageorge kelly.  ainfamous criminals.  ainmates.  amachine gun kelly.  aoutlaws.  apenal policy.  apenitentiary.  aprison administrators.  aprison guards.  aprison.  apublic enemy.  aresistance.  asecurity.  asupermax prison.  athe rock.  aworst of the worst.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025607140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094298140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520942981423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520942981/original  a978-3